1.  Thrashing kab hota hai?
    Thrashing tab hota hai jab system zyada waqt page faults handle karne mein lagata hai aur actual kaam kam hota hai.
    CPU utilization girne lagti hai. Cause = too many processes, not enough memory. Solution = reduce multiprogramming 
    degree ya working set model use karo.
    Interview Tip: Yaad rakho: Thrashing = OS page swap karne mein itna busy ki actual kaam band.

2.  Virtual memory kya hota hai?
    Virtual memory ek illusion create karta hai ki RAM bahut badi hai. Disk ka kuch part (swap space) RAM ki tarah use hota hai.
    Process ko lagta hai poori memory uske liye hai, actually OS pages swap karta rehta hai as needed.
    Interview Tip: Formula: Virtual Memory = RAM + Swap Space on Disk.

3.  Demand Paging kya hota hai aur kaise kaam karta hai?
    Pages tabhi memory mein load hote hain jab unki zaroorat hoti hai (on demand). Process shuru hoti hai bina poori memory load kiye.
    Jab page chahiye aur RAM mein nahi (page fault), OS disk se load karta hai. Efficient but page faults slow hote hain.
    Interview Tip: Steps: Access → Page fault → OS loads page → Execution resumes.

4.  Paging ka basic function kya hai?
    Paging = non-contiguous memory allocation technique. Secondary memory pages mein divided, main memory frames mein divided.
    Har process ke pages available frames mein load hote hain — contiguous hona zaruri nahi. Internal fragmentation ho sakti hai.
    Interview Tip: Key terms: Pages = secondary memory chunks. Frames = RAM chunks (same size).

5.  Fragmentation kya hota hai?
    Memory mein chhote chhote unused gaps ban jaate hain jo itne chhhote hain ki kisi process ko allocate nahi ho sakte.2 types:
    Internal (allocated memory se zyada di di, extra waste) aur External (free memory hai but scattered hai, contiguous block nahi banta).
    Interview Tip: Internal: Paging se hoti hai. External: Variable-size allocation se hoti hai.

6.  Internal aur External Fragmentation mein kya fark hai?
    Internal: Process ko zyada memory allocate ho gayi — allocated block ke andar waste space. Solution: best-fit.
    External: Total free memory enough hai but contiguous block nahi — scattered hai. Solution: compaction, paging, segmentation.
    Interview Tip: Simple: Internal = andar waste. External = bahar scattered waste.

7.  Swapping kya hota hai?
    Blocked processes ko RAM se disk (backing store) par temporarily move karna = swap out. Jab zarurat ho toh wapas RAM mein = swap in.
    Isse zyada processes run ho sakti hain jinhe currently RAM mein fit hona mushkil hota.
    Interview Tip: Analogy: Library mein kam use ki kitabein store room mein rakho, jagah free karo nayi ke liye.

8.  Dynamic Loading kya hota hai?
    Routines tabhi memory mein load hote hain jab unhe call kiya jaye. Jo routines kabhi call nahi hote (jaise error handlers) wo kabhi
    load nahi hote. Memory efficiently use hoti hai — poora program pehle se load nahi hota.
    Interview Tip: vs Demand Paging: Dynamic loading = programmer decide karta hai. Demand paging = OS decide karta hai.

9.  Overlays kya hote hain?
    Purana technique: program ke jo parts ek saath chahiye nahi woh ek doosre ko replace karte hain memory mein. Pehle wala part unload,
    naya load. Ab virtual memory ki wajah se ye technique obsolete hai.
    Interview Tip: Yaad rakho: Overlays = programmer manually memory manage karta tha. Ab OS karta hai.

10. Logical aur Physical address mein kya fark hai?
    Logical address = CPU generate karta hai (virtual address), user dekh sakta hai. Physical address = actual RAM location,
    user nahi dekh sakta. MMU (Memory Management Unit) logical ko physical mein convert karta hai.
    Interview Tip: Easily: Logical = map pe address. Physical = actual jagah.

11. Address Binding kya hota hai?
    Program ke instructions aur data ko actual physical memory locations se associate karna = address binding.
    3 types: Compile-time (pehle se fixed), Load-time (jab load ho), Execution-time (runtime pe, relocation possible).
    Interview Tip: 3 times: Compile → Load → Execute. Modern OS execution-time binding use karta hai.

12. Memory Management ke goals kya hain?
    5 goals: Relocation (process ko koi bhi memory location pe rakho), Protection (ek process doosre ki memory access na kare), 
    Sharing (common code share karo), Logical organization (code/data alag), Physical organization (RAM aur disk ke beech management).
    Interview Tip: RPSLO: Relocation, Protection, Sharing, Logical, Organization.

13. Best page size kya hota hai?
    Koi ek fixed "best" page size nahi hoti — system pe depend karta hai. Factors: page table size, paging overhead, fragmentation,
    disk I/O efficiency. Trade-off hai — bada page = less overhead but more internal fragmentation.
    Interview Tip: Interview answer: "It depends on the workload — typically 4KB to 64KB in modern systems."

14. Compaction kya hota hai?
    External fragmentation solve karne ka ek tarika — scattered free memory blocks ko move karke ek bada contiguous block banana.
    Time-consuming process hai. Paging aur segmentation better alternatives hain.
    Interview Tip: Analogy: Wardrobe mein sab shuffle karo taaki ek side pe saari jagah aajaye.

15. Paging aur Segmentation mein kya fark hai?
    Paging: fixed-size pages, OS handle karta hai, invisible to user, internal fragmentation, faster.
    Segmentation: variable-size segments (code, stack, data), compiler handle karta hai, visible to user, external fragmentation,
    slower. Modern OS dono combine karte hain.
    Interview Tip: Key: Paging = OS ke liye. Segmentation = programmer ke liye (logical divisions).

16. Virtual memory ke advantages kya hain?
    Programs physical RAM se bade ho sakte hain, zyada multiprogramming possible hai, external fragmentation eliminate hoti hai,
    memory allocation easy aur cheap hoti hai, programs apne poore code ke bina run kar sakte hain.
    Interview Tip: Main benefit: RAM se bade programs chalao, cheaply.

17. Locality of Reference kya hota hai?
    Programs ka tendency hai ki thode time ke liye same memory locations access karte hain (temporal locality) ya physically nearby
    memory access karte hain (spatial locality). Cache aur virtual memory isi principle pe kaam karte hain.
    Interview Tip: 2 types: Temporal = same location baar baar. Spatial = nearby locations.

18. Associative Memory aur Cache Memory mein kya fark hai?
    Associative Memory: content se access hoti hai (address se nahi). Bahut fast search.
    Cache Memory: address se access hoti hai,but RAM se fast. Cache frequently used data store karta hai.
    Associative memory TLB (Translation Lookaside Buffer) mein use hoti hai.
    Interview Tip: TLB yaad rakho: TLB = associative memory jo page table entries cache karta hai.

19. Caching kya hota hai?
    Cache ek chhoti, fast memory hai jo frequently used data copy rakhti hai taaki main memory tak baar baar na jaana pade.
    CPU mein L1/L2/L3 cache hoti hai. Cache miss hone pe data main memory se fetch hota hai.
    Interview Tip: Hierarchy: CPU Registers > L1 Cache > L2 Cache > L3 > RAM > Disk.

20. Buffer kya hota hai?
    Buffer ek memory area hai jo do devices ya device aur application ke beech data temporarily store karta hai jab unki speeds
    different hain. Jaise printer buffer — CPU fast hai, printer slow, buffer mein data aata hai pehle.
    Interview Tip: vs Cache: Buffer = speed mismatch handle. Cache = frequently accessed data store.

21. Spooling kya hota hai?
    SPOOL = Simultaneous Peripheral Operations On-Line. Jobs ek buffer (disk pe) mein store hote hain before peripheral device pe jaate hain.
    Printer ka classic example — multiple print jobs spool mein queue hote hain. CPU block nahi hota.
    Interview Tip: Real example: Print queue = spooling. CPU kaam karta rehta hai.

22. Hashed Page Table ke advantages aur disadvantages kya hain?
    Advantages: Synchronization efficient, faster than search trees for lookup, widely used in software (associative arrays, DB indexing,
    caches). Disadvantages: Hash collisions practically unavoidable (need collision resolution), inefficient with many collisions,
    null values supported nahi.
    Interview Tip: Use case: Large address spaces mein regular page table bahut badi hogi — hashed page table efficient alternative.

23. Dynamic memory allocation ke advantages kya hain?
    Jab memory requirement pehle se pata nahi. Data structures without upper limit. Memory efficiently use hoti hai — sirf utni lo jitni
    chahiye. Linked lists aur trees ke liye must. Runtime pe size change possible.
    Interview Tip: Static vs Dynamic: Static = compile time size fixed. Dynamic = runtime pe decide.

24. Belady's Anomaly kya hota hai?
    Usually zyada page frames = kam page faults. Lekin FIFO page replacement mein kabhi kabhi zyada frames dene se page faults badh
    jaate hain — yeh Belady's anomaly hai. LRU aur Optimal page replacement algorithms mein ye anomaly nahi hoti.
    Interview Tip: Simple: FIFO mein zyada memory = more faults (sometimes). FIFO avoid karo — LRU prefer karo.

25. Virtual memory ka performance kaise calculate karte hain?
    Effective Access Time = (1-p) × Memory access time + p × Page fault time. Jahan p = page fault probability. p bahut chhota hona
    chahiye nahi toh performance bahut kharab ho jaati hai. Page fault service time = multiple milliseconds (disk involved).
    Interview Tip: Formula yaad karo: EAT = (1-p)*memory_time + p*page_fault_time.

26. Locality of Reference virtual memory mein kaise help karta hai?
    Kyunki programs thodi si memory ko baar baar access karte hain (working set), virtual memory efficient rahti hai — sirf wo pages
    RAM mein raho jo actually use ho rahe hain. Working set model pe based scheduling thrashing reduce karta hai.
    Interview Tip: Working Set Model: Track karo kaunse pages recently use hue aur woh pages RAM mein rakho.

27. Address binding ke types kya hain?
    3 types: Compile-time (compiler physical address embed kar deta hai — address change nahi ho sakta, rare),
    Load-time (loader assign karta hai jab program load ho — relocatable code),
    Execution-time (runtime pe translate hota hai MMU ke through — modern OS yahi use karta hai, allows relocation).
    Interview Tip: Modern OS = always Execution-time binding kyunki process ko memory move karni pad sakti hai.

28. Swapping vs Paging mein kya fark hai?
    Swapping = poori process ko RAM se disk move karo. Slow but complete. Paging = specific pages move karo as needed. Fine-grained,
    faster, modern approach. Virtual memory paging use karta hai, swapping nahi (though swap space exist karta hai as fallback).
    Interview Tip: Modern Linux: "swap" technically page-level swapping hai — full process swap modern OS mein rare hai.

29. Hashed page table kab use karte hain?
    Large address spaces ke liye (jaise 64-bit systems) jahan regular page table bahut badi ho jaaye. Virtual page number hash table
    mein index karta hai. Chaining handle karta hai collisions ko. Inverted page table ek aur alternative hai — physical frame per 
    entry rakhta hai instead of virtual page per entry.
    Interview Tip: Interview angle: 64-bit address space mein regular page table = terabytes. Hashed ya inverted PT = practical solution.

30. Multiprogramming degree aur thrashing mein kya relationship hai?
    Multiprogramming degree badhao toh CPU utilization badhti hai — ek point tak. Uske baad processes ke paas enough frames nahi hote,
    page faults badh jaate hain, CPU busy pagine swap karne mein, aur utilization crash ho jaati hai. Ye thrashing hai.
    Working set model se optimal degree find karo.
    Interview Tip: Graph shape: CPU utilization = bell curve vs degree of multiprogramming. Thrashing = right side crash.
    
